{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528660"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:45:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:45:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14322"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14322","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14322"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.63,0.06,0.18,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7017"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54595"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7017"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14322"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40112"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1306"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"3069"},{"type":"tags","id":"3557"},{"type":"tags","id":"3870"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16684"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18657"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41946"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54595"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with anxiety, irritability, and difficulty sleeping. He reports these symptoms started three days ago when he abruptly stopped using cannabis. He has been smoking cannabis daily for the past five years and decided to quit due to concerns about his job. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears agitated with a pulse rate of 100/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. He is alert and oriented but restless. There are no signs of intoxication or other substance use.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management strategy for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Admit for inpatient detoxification","Provide supportive care and refer to outpatient addiction services","Start bupropion therapy","Prescribe benzodiazepines for short-term abstinence support","Initiate replacement therapy with synthetic cannabinoids"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is presenting with symptoms consistent with cannabis withdrawal syndrome. The most appropriate management strategy is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eprovide supportive care and refer to outpatient addiction services\u003C/strong\u003E. This approach addresses both the immediate symptoms and the long-term need for support in maintaining abstinence. Supportive care may include education about the expected course of withdrawal, coping strategies, and symptomatic relief. Outpatient addiction services can provide ongoing support, counseling, and relapse prevention strategies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmitting for inpatient detoxification\u003C/strong\u003E is generally not necessary for cannabis withdrawal. Most cases can be managed effectively on an outpatient basis, reserving inpatient care for severe cases or those with significant comorbidities. This patient\u0027s symptoms, while uncomfortable, do not warrant inpatient admission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStarting bupropion therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for cannabis withdrawal. While bupropion has been studied for its potential in treating cannabis use disorder, it is not specifically approved or recommended for managing cannabis withdrawal symptoms. There is insufficient evidence to support its use in this context.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribing benzodiazepines for short-term abstinence support\u003C/strong\u003E, while potentially helpful for managing anxiety and insomnia in the short term, is not the most appropriate first-line approach. Benzodiazepines carry their own risks of dependence and are generally avoided unless other interventions have failed. Non-pharmacological approaches should be prioritized.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInitiating replacement therapy with synthetic cannabinoids\u003C/strong\u003E is not an evidence-based approach for managing cannabis withdrawal and could potentially lead to further substance use issues. There are currently no approved cannabinoid replacement therapies for cannabis withdrawal, unlike nicotine replacement for tobacco cessation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of cannabis withdrawal primarily involves supportive care to address specific symptoms. This may include short-term use of medications for sleep disturbances or anxiety if needed, but the focus should be on non-pharmacological interventions. Psychoeducation about the expected course of withdrawal symptoms, coping strategies, and referral to outpatient addiction services for ongoing support and relapse prevention are crucial components of care. The symptoms of cannabis withdrawal typically peak within the first week of abstinence and gradually improve over the following days to weeks.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cannabis withdrawal syndrome is characterized by irritability, anxiety, sleep disturbances, and decreased appetite.","Management of cannabis withdrawal is primarily supportive, focusing on symptom relief and psychosocial interventions.","There are currently no FDA-approved medications specifically for cannabis withdrawal syndrome."],"references":["Copeland J. Cannabis use and its associated disorders: clinical care. Australian Family Physician. 2016 Dec;45(12):874-7."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40112"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14322"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40112"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-08T08:29:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-08T08:30:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7017"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54595"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"g